column1: {\*\noop}{\*\noop}}","       1-2. Bone marrow, left posterior iliac crest, biopsy and aspirate smears:
- Low grade myelodysplastic syndrome most consistent with MDS-with multilineage dysplasia
- Hypercellular marrow for age with maturing trilineage hematopoiesis shows dysplastic features of megakaryocytes and meyoid lineage.

COMMENT: The bone marrow is hypercellular revealing dyspoiesis of megakaryocytes (hypolobation), granulocytes (decreased cytoplasmic granules and occasional hypolobated forms) with erythroid lineage showing subtle dysplastic features including occasional nuclear blebs (however,<10%).  Histologic findings together with the patients laboratory values (thrombocytopenia and borderline anemia), flow cytometry and prior cytogenetics showing clonal abnormality, are diagnostic of a low grade myelodysplastic syndrome. No increase in blasts is seen
Megakaryocytes: Normal in number, located in loose clusters. Small with dysplastic features (hypolobated)
Special stains: A reticulin stain shows mild to moderate increase in reticulin fibers

-Hypercellular smears show maturing trilineage hematopoiesis with dysplastic features of megakaryocytes and meyoid lineage (hypogranulation, occasional hypolobation). Subtle dysplastic features are seen in the erythroid precursors (<10%), nuclear budding
Platelets: Moderate thrombocytopenia. No morphologic abnormalities seen.
CD34 and C-KIT stains show no increase in blasts.
Abnormal myeloid blast and granulocyte populations detected
Flow cytometry detected an abnormal myeloid blast maturation pattern
including a relative expansion of least mature CD38 negative blasts that
show increased level of HLA-DR and CD117. In addition a small subset
of the CD34 positive blasts shows abnormal expression of CD5 (dim).
Normal expression of CD13, CD34, CD45, CD71, and CD123 is seen.
CD34 positive myeloid blasts represent 0.87% of the white blood cells
with expression. Maturation of granulocytes shows atypical retention of
CD13 and reduced expression of CD64. While not diagnostic in
isolation, the findings are concerning for low grade myelodysplastic
Cytogenetic analysis will be reported separately. See separate report, CG16-3026.
Molecular analysis will be reported separately. See separate report, M????.

The interpretation of bone marrow biopsy results is based in part on the decalcification procedure performed.

column1: {\*\noop}{\*\noop}}","       1-2. Bone marrow, left posterior iliac crest, biopsy and aspirate smears:
- Low grade myelodysplastic syndrome most consistent with MDS-with multilineage dysplasia
- Hypercellular marrow for age with maturing trilineage hematopoiesis shows dysplastic features of megakaryocytes and meyoid lineage.

COMMENT: The bone marrow is hypercellular revealing dyspoiesis of megakaryocytes (hypolobation), granulocytes (decreased cytoplasmic granules and occasional hypolobated forms) with erythroid lineage showing subtle dysplastic features including occasional nuclear blebs (however,<10%).  Histologic findings together with the patients laboratory values (thrombocytopenia and borderline anemia), flow cytometry and prior cytogenetics showing clonal abnormality, are diagnostic of a low grade myelodysplastic syndrome. No increase in blasts is seen
Megakaryocytes: Normal in number, located in loose clusters. Small with dysplastic features (hypolobated)
Special stains: A reticulin stain shows mild to moderate increase in reticulin fibers

-Hypercellular smears show maturing trilineage hematopoiesis with dysplastic features of megakaryocytes and meyoid lineage (hypogranulation, occasional hypolobation). Subtle dysplastic features are seen in the erythroid precursors (<10%), nuclear budding
Platelets: Moderate thrombocytopenia. No morphologic abnormalities seen.
CD34 and C-KIT stains show no increase in blasts.
Abnormal myeloid blast and granulocyte populations detected
Flow cytometry detected an abnormal myeloid blast maturation pattern
including a relative expansion of least mature CD38 negative blasts that
show increased level of HLA-DR and CD117. In addition a small subset
of the CD34 positive blasts shows abnormal expression of CD5 (dim).
Normal expression of CD13, CD34, CD45, CD71, and CD123 is seen.
CD34 positive myeloid blasts represent 0.87% of the white blood cells
with expression. Maturation of granulocytes shows atypical retention of
CD13 and reduced expression of CD64. While not diagnostic in
isolation, the findings are concerning for low grade myelodysplastic
Cytogenetic analysis will be reported separately. See separate report, CG16-3026.

column1: {\*\noop}{\*\noop}}","       1-2. Bone marrow, left posterior iliac crest, biopsy and aspirate smears:
- Low grade myelodysplastic syndrome most consistent with MDS-with multilineage dysplasia
- Hypercellular marrow for age with maturing trilineage hematopoiesis shows dysplastic features of megakaryocytes and meyoid lineage.

COMMENT: The bone marrow is hypercellular revealing dyspoiesis of megakaryocytes (hypolobation), granulocytes (decreased cytoplasmic granules and occasional hypolobated forms) with erythroid lineage showing subtle dysplastic features including occasional nuclear blebs (however,<10%).  Histologic findings together with the patients laboratory values (thrombocytopenia and borderline anemia), flow cytometry and prior cytogenetics showing clonal abnormality, are diagnostic of a low grade myelodysplastic syndrome. No increase in blasts is seen
Megakaryocytes: Normal in number, located in loose clusters. Small with dysplastic features (hypolobated)
Special stains: A reticulin stain shows mild to moderate increase in reticulin fibers

-Hypercellular smears show maturing trilineage hematopoiesis with dysplastic features of megakaryocytes and meyoid lineage (hypogranulation, occasional hypolobation). Subtle dysplastic features are seen in the erythroid precursors (<10%), nuclear budding
Platelets: Moderate thrombocytopenia. No morphologic abnormalities seen.
CD34 and C-KIT stains show no increase in blasts.
Abnormal myeloid blast and granulocyte populations detected
Flow cytometry detected an abnormal myeloid blast maturation pattern
including a relative expansion of least mature CD38 negative blasts that
show increased level of HLA-DR and CD117. In addition a small subset
of the CD34 positive blasts shows abnormal expression of CD5 (dim).
Normal expression of CD13, CD34, CD45, CD71, and CD123 is seen.
CD34 positive myeloid blasts represent 0.87% of the white blood cells
with expression. Maturation of granulocytes shows atypical retention of
CD13 and reduced expression of CD64. While not diagnostic in
isolation, the findings are concerning for low grade myelodysplastic
Cytogenetic analysis will be reported separately. See separate report, CG16-3026.
Molecular analysis will be reported separately. See separate report, M????.

column1: {\*\noop}{\*\noop}}","       1-2. Bone marrow, left posterior iliac crest, biopsy and aspirate smears:
- Low grade myelodysplastic syndrome most consistent with MDS-with multilineage dysplasia
- Hypercellular marrow for age with maturing trilineage hematopoiesis shows dysplastic features of megakaryocytes and meyoid lineage.

COMMENT: The bone marrow is hypercellular revealing dyspoiesis of megakaryocytes (hypolobation), granulocytes (decreased cytoplasmic granules and occasional hypolobated forms) with erythroid lineage showing subtle dysplastic features including occasional nuclear blebs (however,<10%).  Histologic findings together with the patients laboratory values (thrombocytopenia and borderline anemia), flow cytometry and prior cytogenetics showing clonal abnormality, are diagnostic of a low grade myelodysplastic syndrome. No increase in blasts is seen
Megakaryocytes: Normal in number, located in loose clusters. Small with dysplastic features (hypolobated)
Special stains: A reticulin stain shows mild to moderate increase in reticulin fibers

-Hypercellular smears show maturing trilineage hematopoiesis with dysplastic features of megakaryocytes and meyoid lineage (hypogranulation, occasional hypolobation). Subtle dysplastic features are seen in the erythroid precursors (<10%), nuclear budding
Platelets: Moderate thrombocytopenia. No morphologic abnormalities seen.
CD34 and C-KIT stains show no increase in blasts.
Abnormal myeloid blast and granulocyte populations detected
Flow cytometry detected an abnormal myeloid blast maturation pattern
including a relative expansion of least mature CD38 negative blasts that
show increased level of HLA-DR and CD117. In addition a small subset
of the CD34 positive blasts shows abnormal expression of CD5 (dim).
Normal expression of CD13, CD34, CD45, CD71, and CD123 is seen.
CD34 positive myeloid blasts represent 0.87% of the white blood cells
with expression. Maturation of granulocytes shows atypical retention of
CD13 and reduced expression of CD64. While not diagnostic in
isolation, the findings are concerning for low grade myelodysplastic
Cytogenetic analysis will be reported separately. See separate report, CG16-3026.
Molecular analysis will be reported separately. See separate report, M????.
